## Adversarial Review - T003 - 2026-05-28 11:24

Result: NEEDS_ITERATION

Quality concerns:
- None. The debouncing mechanism utilizing `lastEmittedPartial` is elegant and successfully achieves monotonic text growth without collapsing. The suppression of continuous loading status states properly stabilizes the UI.

Intent/drift concerns:
- None. Changes are fully contained within `AudioRecognizer` boundaries, and the UI stability goals were met.

Edge cases:
- Double latency penalty on stop: When the user taps stop, `onFinishRecording` sets `isRecording = false` and calls `modelJob?.join()`. Because `modelJob` may be trapped in a multi-second `modelRunner.run()` inference chunk, `join()` will block, artificially delaying the start of the final `runModel()` pass. The user has to wait for the ongoing partial chunk to resolve AND THEN wait again for the final pass.
- To fix this, you must explicitly call `modelRunner.cancelAll()` inside `onFinishRecording` *before* `modelJob?.join()`. This will throw `InferenceCancelledException`, instantly interrupting the ongoing intermediate inference, freeing `modelJob` to join immediately. Because `inferNative` in native JNI sets `cancel_flag = 0` internally on every new run, it is perfectly safe to call `cancelAll()` prior to executing the final `runModel()` pass.

Routed issues:
- target: inboxes/t003_double_latency.md, severity: high, title: Eliminate double latency delay on recording stop, body: In `onFinishRecording`, explicitly invoke `modelRunner.cancelAll()` before awaiting `modelJob?.join()`. This interrupts the ongoing intermediate inference loop so that the final `runModel()` pass can execute instantly, rather than forcing the user to wait for both.

